# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: charles-m-schwab
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] The **20th Century Press Archives** (German: *Pressearchiv 20.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert*) comprises about 19 million newspaper clippings, organized in folders about persons, companies, wares, events and topics.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] It originates from the Hamburg Kolonialinstitut (colonial institute) founded in 1908.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] Within the Hamburg Institute of International Economics (HWWA) it turned into a unique public press archive.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] In 2007 it was absorbed by the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) and merged with the Wirtschaftsarchiv (economics archive) of the Kiel Institute for the World Economy (IfW), founded in 1914.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] Article collection was discontinued at the end of 2005, but the archive is still open to the public.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] The archive has its origins in two institutions in the German cities of Hamburg and Kiel.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] In Hamburg, after a few years, the "Zentralstelle" (central office) of the Kolonialinstitut was transformed from a free information center for colonial issues into a comprehensive archive of global political and economic topics, which primarily supported the city's merchants.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] After the breakdown of the German colonial empire in World War I, the renaming to "Hamburgisches Welt-Wirtschafts-Archiv" in 1919 sealed this reorientation.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] The staff of HWWA reflected its importance and grew from 54 in 1919 to 183 permanent or temporary employees in 1958 – a number that seems to have remained largely stable until the late 1990s.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] Founded shortly before the outbreak of the First World War, the Kiel Economic Archive and its library were closely linked to the scientific work of the IfW, which focused on global economic contexts and their practical use.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] In 1966, the library of the IfW was given the function of a central library for economics by the German Research Foundation (DFG) in the Federal Republic of Germany, and in 1993, the department was renamed accordingly.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] During the first and second world wars, both archives were intensively involved in the foreign and wartime planning of the empire and the Nazi state.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] Starting in 1936, "Confidential Reports from the Foreign Press" provided selected economic leaders and Nazi departments with "largely unfiltered information and comments on economic issues from foreign media and represented a unique feature in Nazi media policy".
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] Acting with the informal means of a foreign cultural and information policy supplementing the military expansion policy, HWWA and IfW dedicated their services to the Nazi regime.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] In 1996, a closer cooperation between HWWA and ZBW / Wirtschaftsarchiv began, with the aim of merging the two archives.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] From the beginning of 2001, the articles were indexed according to a new common classification system and made retrievable via a reference database, "EconPress".
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] Following a recommendation from an evaluation within the Leibniz Association in 2003, the current press documentation was finished at the end of 2005 and the materials were frozen at that point.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] The separate existence of the HWWA ended in 2007 with the integration of its press documentation and library into the ZBW as a newly formed foundation under public law.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] Today, the press archive belongs to the (research) organisations of the Leibniz Association.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] By 1919 at the latest, the Hamburg archive collected "press clippings on a global scale".
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] More than 1400 sources were monitored for the press archives.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] Their broad international distribution provides access to the history of political thought and receptive history of the covered topics.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] Occasionally, the collected publications go back as far as 1826.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] While the persons archive was only available in paper form until its partial digitization, the holdings of the topics, wares and companies archives were saved every ten years on roll film or microfiche since the 1960s and then the paper clippings were pulped.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] The holdings of the Kiel Wirtschaftsarchiv are less comprehensively documented.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] The "war archive" of 1914–1918, which amounted to one million clippings, was destroyed by a bomb strike in 1942.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] In 1958, when six scientific experts and more than 30 employees in total were collecting and organizing the material, the total extent of the archive was estimated as more than three million, and in 1993 as more than ten million.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert* application, parts of the holdings of both archives are now accessible on the web.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] From 2004 to 2007, the German Research Foundation funded a project to digitize parts of the archives, namely the materials from the beginning up to 1949 (the formation of the Federal Republic of Germany).
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] The paper clippings from the folders of the persons archive were scanned, and metadata (folder and document ID as well as page number, occasionally also source, publication date, author and title) were recorded by project staff.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] Optical character recognition could not be applied due to the partially used Fraktur scripts, the constantly changing fonts (as well as languages) in the sequence of the articles, and the sometimes poor quality of the clippings.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] However, the approximately 5,500 person folders created before 1949 are fully accessible online.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] The roll film parts of the archive (up to 1960) have also been digitized.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] As neither the folders nor the documents on these films were separated in a machine-readable fashion, such formal elements could not be automatically derived.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] Instead, the pages had to be "sliced" with specially developed "Slider" software, assembled into documents and folders, and given metadata.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] Only a small part of this labor-intensive process was finished at the end of the project in 2007.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] It is continued today, so that new folders are continually made available via the web application "Pressemappe 20.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert", which was created within the framework of the project.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] 11,000 company folders on digitized roll film, by 2018 about 7,500 were accessible online.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] For the topics and wares archives, the proportion of online folders seems to be significantly lower.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] The persons are alphabetically indexed by name, while the companies are accessible by name, geographically by their headquarters and via industry lists.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] The topics can be accessed via the topics hierarchy and country system as well as through a search for subject and geographical GND keywords, and via a world map with geolocations.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] The limitation to 1949 was made for capacity reasons, and due to intellectual property rights restrictions.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] Numerous individual articles within the dossiers are subject to blocking notices if the death of the author (or in the case of anonymous or pseudonymous works, the date of publication) is less than 70 years ago.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] With a moving wall more and more documents should be released over time.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] How many of the about 5.7 million documents digitized in the context of the project are accessible to the scientific and general public on the web is not known.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] In 2019, the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) placed all the metadata of the archives under a CC0 licence, and began a cooperation and "data donation" with Wikimedia Deutschland.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] This led to the creation of many new Wikidata items and the enrichment of many existing items; by the end of 2022, every folder in the archive was connected to items in Wikidata.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] In 2024, changes to intellectual property rights in Europe made it possible to provide complete digitized images from the archive – some 3.8 million pages – for online viewing within the European Union.
[src:charles-m-schwab/20th-century-press-archives] A volunteer project is working on adding links to the archive's folders in Wikidata, so that Wikidata provides an index to the material.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Müller was born on March 29, 1862, at Airolo, Switzerland, to a prominent patrician family that by the 18th and 19th centuries included mercenaries, lawyers, hoteliers and businessmen.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] The family spoke Airolese mainly, a local dialect of Ticinese Italian, as well as Swiss-German.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] His known early work is necessarily varied, and includes pictures in the style of Deschwanden (usually signed **Müller, Adolfo**), academic drawings executed in Munich (usually signed **Ad.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Müller**), copies of Old Masters, and early independent oils, sometimes was influenced by artists like Robert Zünd and Frank Buchser, which includes landscapes, genre and religious pictures.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Many of these survive in the ancestral home of the Müllers in Hospental, Switzerland, and with surviving members of his family in the St Gotthard and elsewhere.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] While in Paris in late 1884, he decided to visit the United States.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] He arrived first in Milwaukee, and then visited Chicago and St Paul, Minnesota, where he had relatives.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] In 1885 he went to Baltimore to paint James Cardinal Gibbons for the first time and in 1886 completed a full-length portrait which was given to the Cardinal for his residence after being exhibited at Schaus's Gallery in New York (missing).
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] At around this time he was travelling all over the eastern United States painting and executed a very large canvas of the Bushkill Falls in Pennsylvania (Von der Heydt Museum, Wuppertal, Germany).
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Luckily for the artist, his talent for portraiture was soon noticed by the St.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Hill, who was to commission or acquire many pictures of himself, his family, his friends and business associates, like the Canadian missionary Father Albert Lacombe in 1895, and John Stewart Kennedy the financier in 1901.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] In the Newark Museum, New Jersey, is a portrait of a little girl dressed in pink called Miss Brandeis which is probably his first commissioned picture made in America (it is signed with a variation of his family name, **A.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Lombardi-Muller**), though a portrait of Father Joseph Fransioli, who was minister to the large influx of Italian-speaking immigrants arriving in New York, today at the Brooklyn Historical Society, was possibly completed before this as it is signed **Adolph Muller**.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] It would seem that from quite early on he wanted to sign his works in a way that was unique to him, and so portraits between 1886 and 1889 are sometimes signed **F.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] By 1890 this was fully anglicized as **A.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Muller-Ury**, the umlaut in his surname being dropped.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Some of his later smaller works are signed **A M Ury**.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] (As late as 1932, the Swiss-American Historical Society published a book on Swiss-Americans where his name was inaccurately stated as Adolph Felix Muller-Uri.) In 1889 he painted a portrait of John R.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Brady a New York Judge which was apparently presented to the American Bar Association.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] In 1890 he completed a second bust-length portrait of Father Joseph Fransioli of Brooklyn (lost).
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] His New York studio 1885–1904 was in the Sherwood Studio Building, 58 West 57th Street and 6th Avenue (the building has been long demolished), where he is noted before 1889 in Room C; by 1894 he had a studio with a waiting room (both lit by windows) and a bedroom.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Other artists who rented studios in the building in the 1880s were his friend from Munich, Jan Chełmiński (who later married the sister of art dealer Roland Knoedler), landscape painter Robert W.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Van Boskerck, James Carroll Beckwith, painter and muralist Edwin Howland Blashfield, and painter turned critic Arthur Hoeber, and later artists such as Carle Blenner and portraitist George Burroughs Torrey.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] He was photographed in his Sherwood studio by artist turned photographer Edwin Scott Bennett (1847–1915) which was exhibited at the annual exhibition of the Society of Amateur Photographers of New York in 1894.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] For a number of years he commuted between New York and Europe.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] In 1892, after the great success of his portraits of Senator Chauncey Depew in 1890 (Yale Club of New York City) and Mrs Theodore Havemeyer in 1891 (now the property of the Preservation Society of Newport County, Rhode Island), he applied for United States citizenship.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] It was apparently at this date that he met the young art dealer Joseph Duveen, who was to become a close friend, and after 1891 that he began to be dubbed 'Painter to the Four Hundred', referring to the elite of New York society in whose circles he socialized.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] He was much aided by the Havemeyers, and also by Louis Benziger (1840–1896), a Roman Catholic publisher (Benziger Brothers), who persuaded many New Yorkers to sit for him; he remained friendly with his son Bruno Benziger until his death, and indeed Bruno Benziger organized the artist's burial.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] For three years in the late 1890s he leased one of the studios in Pembroke Studios in Kensington, London, where he certainly painted portraits of Donald Smith, 1st Baron Strathcona and Mount Royal, and Lord Mount Stephen who were business associates of James J.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Hill, of whom he made an etching in London in 1898 which was distributed to Hill's family and colleagues.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] According to a letter he wrote to Hill he started the portrait of Consuelo Yznaga, the 8th Duchess of Manchester, in London in 1898, but it is not known if it was ever completed.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] In 1903 he was one of a group of artists who invested in a new studio building, the Atelier Building, 33 West 67th Street.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Muller-Ury lived in the top floor right studio, and incorporated a stained glass panel of the Müller coat-of-arms into the window (removed in 1947 and now at the Haus Müller in Hospental, Switzerland).
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] The floors were all inlaid with borders of intarsia, and the smaller windows given mullions.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] He moved into the studio in 1904 and remained there until 1947.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] He also painted the first permanent diplomatic representative of Switzerland in the United Kingdom, then Swiss Minister in London, Dr Charles Daniel Bourcart of Basel (now at the Swiss Embassy in London).
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] In 1896 A Boston newspaper reported that, ‘...
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Müller-Ury, the portrait painter, who has just returned from abroad, has taken an attractive studio in Everett street, Newport, the one occupied by Mr.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] In a surviving photograph of the artist’s studio in the Sherwood taken in 1894 (a portrait of Monsignor Satolli is on the easel next to it) there is huge still life, and in a letter from his studio to James J.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Hill dated 12 August 1895 (Hill Papers, St.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Paul, MN) he says that he hopes that the 'flower peace [sic]' he sent to him 'will suit for the place intended for', further evidence that he had painted some still lifes before 1896.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] After 1918 the style of his still lifes becomes more impressionistic, the technique more painterly and using a great deal of impasto, and usually depict roses in Chinese vases from the former collection of J.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] The roses were claimed by the soprano Jessica Dragonette in her autobiography to be the varieties American Beauty (red), La France (pink), Belle of Portugal (pale pink), Claudius, Killarney (rose pink), and Boucher-Pierné, but there were others.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Many of his impressionistic rose paintings were created after he moved to California.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] In March 1922 he travelled with Sir Joseph Duveen (later Lord Duveen) to California for the first time, in order that Duveen could deliver to bibliophile and art collector Henry E.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Huntington Gainsborough's famous picture *The Blue Boy* which Huntington had bought the previous year.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Duveen had promised the artist that Huntington would commission a portrait of himself.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Müller-Ury liked California and after painting Archbishop Edward Joseph Hanna in San Francisco in 1923 decided the following year to erect a studio near Huntington's estate.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] The studio he built was at the corner of Monterey and Shenandoah Roads in San Marino (architect Carleton Winslow), in the fashionable Spanish style with a green tiled roof and in the studio an enormous north-facing window.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] He placed the Muller coat-of-arms on the east frontage, where it may be found today.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] The gardens were extensively planted with many varieties of roses including Radiance, Columbia, Rose Marie, Irish Charm, Imperial Potentate and American Beauty which he painted into his canvases depicting the Morgan porcelains begun in New York.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Duveen built a bungalow next door to the artist on Shenandoah Road, but seems to have quickly sold it after the death of his client Henry E.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] In 1926, Müller-Ury seems to have begun from a photograph of a portrait of Henry E.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] In 1930, Müller-Ury painted the former Miss Gladys Quarré of San Francisco (then Mrs Frederick Peabody of Montecito, Santa Barbara); later she became known as Gladys Quarré Knapp, a socialite and friend of many Hollywood actors.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] He also painted a large allegorical work entitled *The Spirit of California* a version of which was acquired by a prominent art collector called Fred Elbridge Keeler (lost).
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Müller-Ury abandoned the studio for the last time on September 3, 1933, after which it was let to friends.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] The house was apparently used by the Red Cross during the Second World War.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] He sold it in January 1947 for about half its value because nobody was prepared at that time to buy a property where most rooms were comparatively small except for the enormous studio.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] After his return from California he settled permanently back in his New York studio.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] In 1936 he travelled to Europe and he may have done so in 1937 and certainly in 1938 when he painted a large portrait of President Motta of Switzerland, for his home town of Bellinzona (Archivio Cantonale).
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] In 1937 he painted a portrait of Ellen Dunlap Hopkins, founder of the New York School of Applied Design for Women which he presented to the School in 1938 (Private collection, Brooklyn).
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] In 1940, he painted the then-famous radio soprano Jessica Dragonette (Georgian Court College, New Jersey) and several times thereafter, his last portrait in 1946 depicting her bust-length in a gold fez.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] In 1941 he produced a portrait of her sister Rosalinda (always called Nadea) Loftus looking over her shoulder.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] He also painted Dragonette's colleague Fred Mitchell, and several portraits of her friends and acquaintances.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] In 1942, at age 80, he painted a three-quarter length seated portrait of Mrs George H.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Ingalls (née Katharine Davis Hinkle), whose late husband, a descendant of one of the founder families of America who had left Lincolnshire in 1628, had been a Vice-President of the New York Central Railroad.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Müller-Ury died, apparently of cancer, on July 6, 1947, at the Lenox Hill Hospital, New York and is buried in New Calvary Cemetery, Queens, New York, where his gravestone is marked simply, if incorrectly, 'ADOLPH MULLER-URY 1862–1947'.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] On Thursday, July 10, 1947, a Requiem Mass was held for the artist in St.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] After his death his youngest brother Otto Müller travelled to New York to settle his estate.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Most of his studio contents, and a good many of his pictures, were sold in two sales at the Plaza Art Galleries, 28 and 29 November 1947 (No.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] 2813), including his oil sketch of Kaiser Wilhelm II of Germany, and the portrait of Lina Cavalieri.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] The Frick Art Reference Library, New York, has a copy of both catalogues, where the prices for his pictures are marked; three extra lots were included in the second sale.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Hill and Senator Chauncey Depew and was donated to Wyoming by Nicholas M.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Turner, husband of the soprano Jessica Dragonette, who at one time owned nearly forty pictures by the artist many bought at his studio sale in 1947).
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] They also acquired from Wyoming the artist's hands modelled by Gertrude Colburn (died 1968).
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] The National Portrait Gallery in Washington has nine portraits, including President William McKinley, General Henry Clarke Corbin, James J.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Hill and Chauncey Depew, and two oils that the American Heritage Center at the University of Wyoming in Laramie gave them in 2007 from the Dragonette Collection: a Self-portrait and a portrait of steel titan Charles M.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] In 2009 they acquired a drawing of Anaconda Copper Mining Millionaire Marcus Daly.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] The New York State Museum at Albany contains six portraits, five of which were in the former New York Chamber of Commerce: Theodore Havemeyer, Oswald Ottendorfer, James Constable, William 'Boyce' Thompson, and Benjamin Altman.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Much of his work remains in private collections or with the descendants of his sitters, and many of the portraits of his most famous sitters are apparently lost.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] However, his recently rediscovered 1923 portrait of his great friend Sir Joseph Duveen, the art dealer, has been recently widely reproduced, notably on the cover of the 2004 biography of Duveen by Meryle Secrest; it was subsequently sold at TEFAF Maastricht in 2006 for $95,000.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Hildegarde Muller-Uri (born 1894, Greenwich Village, New York City – died 1990) – actually born Hildegarde Petronella Bernhardina Muller – an American visual artist, was a relative, and in fact a third cousin, of Müller-Ury.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] She was the eldest daughter of amateur artist Henry Muller and his wife Wilhelmina, both of whom were of course natives of Canton Uri in Switzerland.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Henry Muller had moved from New York to San Augustine in around 1898 to work as a chef in one of Henry Flagler's hotels, and later became to builder and owner of the Hotel Marion at 128 Bay Street.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Breckinridge (1870–1937) at the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts and at the Breckenridge Art School in East Gloucester, Massachusetts, between 1925 and 1930, and later at the Art Students League with Frank Vincent Dumond (1865–1951) and possibly with Olinsky, Lewis, and others.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] She exhibited at the Society of Independent Artists 1929 to 1931.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] By 1937 she had become interested in portraiture and studied again with Wayman Adams (1883–1959) and at some point with his teacher Jossey Bilan.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] She served as president of the San Augustine Art Association in 1947–1948, and was to be president and treasurer of the Florida Association of Art.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Her parents were major patrons of the Arts Club and, in fact, assisted the club by selling them land they owned bordering Marine, Charlotte and Cadiz Streets at a below-market price.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] They then loaned the Arts Club the money to erect a building, essentially designed by Hildegarde Muller-Uri and her father, which was completed in 1954.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Muller-Uri's work includes stained glass, etchings, illustrations, woodblock prints and linoleum cuts of city scenes and historic buildings in Florida.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] In 1955 she was working on a book with twenty-two woodcuts called *St.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] She died in 1990 and was buried in Evergreen Cemetery.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Several of her works have been sold at auction, including *St.
[src:charles-m-schwab/adolfo-müller-ury] Augustine Street Scene depicting a Black Woman Outside a St.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] The son of an Irish American mother and a Civil War–veteran Italian American father, Smith was born and raised on the Lower East Side of Manhattan, New York City, near the Brooklyn Bridge.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] He resided in that neighborhood for his entire life.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Although Smith remained personally untarnished by corruption, he—like many other New York Democrats—was linked to the notorious Tammany Hall political machine that controlled New York City politics during his era.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith served in the New York State Assembly from 1904 to 1915 and was the speaker of the Assembly in 1913.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] He also served as the sheriff of New York County from 1916 to 1917.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] He was first elected governor in 1918, lost his 1920 bid for re-election, and was elected again in 1922, 1924, and 1926.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith was the foremost urban leader of the efficiency movement in the U.S. and was noted for achieving a wide range of reforms as governor.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith was the first Catholic to be the nominee for the U.S. presidency of a major party.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] His 1928 presidential candidacy mobilized both Catholic and anti-Catholic voters.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Many Protestants, particularly German Lutherans and Southern Baptists, feared his candidacy, believing that the pope in Rome would dictate his policies.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith was also a committed "wet" (i.e., an opponent of Prohibition); as governor he had repealed New York State's prohibition law.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith attracted voters who wanted beer, wine, and liquor and did not like dealing with criminal bootleggers, along with voters who were outraged that new criminal gangs had taken over the streets in most large and medium-sized cities.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Hoover, who was the incumbent Republican secretary of commerce, was aided by national prosperity, the absence of American involvement in war, and anti-Catholicism, and he defeated Smith in a landslide in 1928.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith then entered business in New York City, and became involved in the construction and promotion of the Empire State Building.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] He sought the 1932 Democratic presidential nomination, but was defeated by Franklin D.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Roosevelt, his former ally and successor as governor.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] During the Roosevelt presidency, Smith became an increasingly vocal opponent of Roosevelt's New Deal.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith was born at 174 South Street and raised in the Fourth Ward on the Lower East Side of Manhattan in 1873; he resided there for his entire life.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] His mother, Catherine (née Mulvihill), was the daughter of Maria Marsh and Thomas Mulvihill, who were immigrants from County Westmeath, Ireland.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] His father, baptised Joseph Alfred Smith in 1839, was the son of Emanuel Smith, an Italian *marinaro* (sailor).
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] The elder Alfred Smith (Anglicized name for Alfredo Emanuele Ferraro) was the son of Italian and German immigrants.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] He served with the 11th New York Fire Zouaves in the opening months of the Civil War.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith grew up with his family struggling financially in the Gilded Age; New York City matured and completed major infrastructure projects.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] The Brooklyn Bridge was being constructed nearby.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] "The Brooklyn Bridge and I grew up together", Smith would later recall.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] His four grandparents were of ethnic German, Irish as well as Italian ancestry, but Smith identified more with the Irish-American community and became its leading spokesman in the 1920s.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] His father Alfred owned a small trucking firm, but died when Smith was 13.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] James parochial school to help support the family, and worked at a fish market for seven years.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Prior to dropping out of school, he served as an altar boy, and was strongly influenced by the Catholic priests he worked with.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] He never attended high school or college, and claimed he learned about people by studying them at the Fulton Fish Market, where he worked for $12 per week.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] His acting skills made him a success on the amateur theater circuit.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] He became widely known, and developed the smooth oratorical style that characterized his political career.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] In his political career, Smith built on his working-class beginnings, identifying himself with immigrants and campaigning as a man of the people.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Although indebted to the Tammany Hall political machine (and particularly to its boss, "Silent" Charlie Murphy), he remained untarnished by corruption and worked for the passage of progressive legislation.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] It was during his early unofficial jobs with Tammany Hall that he gained renown as an orator.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith's first political job was in 1895, as an investigator in the office of the Commissioner of Jurors as appointed by Tammany Hall.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] A “New Era Progressive”, Smith advocated local government funded facilities and services such as hospitals, parks and schools in poor and working-class areas.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Speaking of the role of the state in 1927, Smith said: "The State is a living force.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] It must have the ability to clothe itself with human understanding of the daily, living needs of those whom it is created to serve." However, Smith envisioned a progressive vision based on state and local intervention, and decentralizing power to specific locales and communities.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] He was ambivalent with regard to federal economic intervention, which eventually led him to oppose the New Deal legislation.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith was first elected to the New York State Assembly (New York Co., 2nd D.) in 1904, and was repeatedly elected to office, serving through 1915.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] After being approached by Frances Perkins, an activist, to improve labor practices, Smith sought to improve the conditions of factory workers.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith served as vice chairman of the state commission appointed to investigate factory conditions after 146 workers died in the 1911 Triangle Shirtwaist Factory fire.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Meeting the families of the deceased Triangle factory workers left a strong impression on him.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Wagner, Smith crusaded against dangerous and unhealthy workplace conditions and championed corrective legislation.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] The Commission, chaired by State Senator Robert F.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Wagner, held a series of widely publicized investigations around the state, interviewing 222 witnesses and taking 3,500 pages of testimony.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] They hired field agents to do on-site inspections of factories.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Starting with the issue of fire safety, they studied broader issues of the risks of injury in the factory environment.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Their findings led to thirty-eight new laws regulating labor in New York State, and gave each of them a reputation as leading progressive reformers working on behalf of the working class.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] In the process, they changed Tammany's reputation from mere corruption to progressive endeavors to help the workers.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] New York City's Fire Chief John Kenlon told the investigators that his department had identified more than 200 factories where conditions resulted in risk of a fire like that at the Triangle Factory.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] In the years from 1911 to 1913, sixty of the sixty-four new laws recommended by the Commission were legislated with the support of Governor William Sulzer.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] In 1911, the Democrats obtained a majority of seats in the State Assembly, and Smith became Majority Leader and Chairman of the Committee on Ways and Means.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] The following year, following the loss of the majority, he became the Minority Leader.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] When the Democrats reclaimed the majority after the next election, he was elected Speaker for the 1913 session.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] He became Minority Leader again in 1914 and 1915.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] In November 1915, he was elected Sheriff of New York County, New York.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] By now he was a leader of the Progressive movement in New York City and state.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] His campaign manager and top aide was Belle Moskowitz, a daughter of Jewish immigrants.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] After serving in the patronage-rich job of sheriff of New York County beginning in 1916, Smith was elected governor of New York in 1918 with the help of Tammany Boss Charles F.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Farley, who brought Smith the upstate vote.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] In 1919, Smith gave the famous speech "A man as low and mean as I can picture", making a drastic break with publisher William Randolph Hearst.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Hearst, known for his notoriously sensationalist and largely left-wing position in the state Democratic Party, was the leader of its populist wing in the city.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] He had combined with Tammany Hall in electing the local administration, and had attacked Smith for starving children by not reducing the cost of milk.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith lost his bid for re-election in the 1920 New York gubernatorial election, but was again elected governor in 1922, 1924 and 1926, with Farley managing his campaign.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] In his 1922 re-election, he embraced his position as an anti-prohibitionist.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith offered alcohol to guests at the Executive Mansion in Albany, and repealed the state's Prohibition enforcement statute, the Mullan-Gage law.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] As governor, Smith became known nationally as a progressive who sought to make government more efficient and more effective in meeting social needs.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith's assistant Robert Moses built the nation's first state park system and reformed the civil service, later gaining appointment as Secretary of State of New York.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] During Smith's time in office, New York strengthened laws governing workers' compensation, women's pensions and children and women's labor with the help of Frances Perkins, soon to be President Franklin D.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] In 1924, Smith unsuccessfully sought the Democratic nomination for president, advancing the cause of civil liberty by decrying lynching and racial violence.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] The party was hopelessly split between the two.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] An increasingly chaotic convention balloted 100 times before both men accepted that neither would be able to win the required two-thirds of the votes, and so each withdrew.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] On the 103rd ballot, the exhausted party nominated the little-known candidate John W.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Davis of West Virginia, a former congressman and United States Ambassador to Great Britain who had been a dark horse presidential candidate in 1920.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Davis lost the election by a landslide to Republican incumbent Calvin Coolidge, who won in part because of the prosperous times.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Undeterred, Smith returned to fight a determined campaign for the party's nomination in 1928.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] He was aided by the endorsement of Philip La Follette, son of 1924 Progressive Party presidential candidate Robert M.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] La Follette, who died in 1925 seven months after receiving 16.62 percent of the popular vote—the fifth-highest proportion for any third-party presidential candidate.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Reporter Frederick William Wile made the oft-repeated observation that Smith was defeated by "the three P's: Prohibition, Prejudice and Prosperity".
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] The Republican Party was still benefiting from an economic boom, as well as a failure to reapportion Congress and the electoral college following the 1920 census, which had registered a 15 percent increase in the urban population.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] The party was biased toward small-town and rural areas.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Its presidential candidate Herbert Hoover, who headed the Census of 1920, did little to alter this state of affairs.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Historians agree that prosperity, along with widespread anti-Catholic sentiment against Smith, made Hoover's election inevitable.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] He defeated Smith by a landslide in the 1928 United States presidential election, carrying five Southern states via crossover voting by conservative white Democrats.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] The fact that Smith was Catholic and the descendant of Catholic immigrants was instrumental in his loss of the election of 1928.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Historical hostilities between Protestants and Catholics had been carried by national groups to the United States by immigrants, and centuries of Protestant domination allowed myths and superstitions about Catholicism to flourish.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Long-established Protestants had viewed the waves of Catholic immigrants from Ireland, Italy and Eastern Europe since the mid-19th century with suspicion.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] In addition, many Protestants carried old fears related to extravagant claims of one religion against the other which dated back to the European wars of religion.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] They feared that Smith would answer to the Pope rather than the United States Constitution.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Scott Farris notes that the anti-Catholicism of American society was the sole reason behind Smith's defeat, as even contemporary Prohibition activists would admit that their main problem with the Democratic candidate was his faith and not any political view.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] A Methodist newspaper in Georgia called Catholicism "a degenerate type of Christianity," while Southern Baptist newspapers ordered their readers to vote against Smith, claiming that he would close down Protestant churches, end freedom of worship and prohibit reading the Bible.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Charles Hillman Fountain, a Protestant writer, insisted that Catholics should be barred from holding any office.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Farris states that "More disturbing than the ridiculous and the dangerous was the respectable anti-Catholicism", as contemporary newspapers and Protestant churches tried to mask their anti-Catholicism as genuine concern.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Protestant activists insisted that Catholicism represents an alien culture and medieval mentality, claiming that Catholicism is incompatible with American democracy and institutions.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Catholics were portrayed as reactionary despite being more centrist than mainstream American Protestant congregations at the time.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] White rural conservatives in the South also believed that Smith's close association with Tammany Hall, the Democratic machine in Manhattan, showed that he tolerated corruption in government, while they overlooked their own brands of it.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Another major controversial issue was the continuation of Prohibition, the enforcement of which was widely considered problematic.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith personally favored the relaxation or repeal of Prohibition laws because they had given rise to more criminality.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] The Democratic Party split North and South on the issue, with the more rural South continuing to favor Prohibition.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] During the campaign, Smith tried to duck the issue with non-committal statements.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith was an articulate proponent of good government and efficiency, as was Hoover.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith swept the entire Catholic vote, which in 1920 and 1924 had been split between the parties; he attracted millions of Catholics, generally ethnic whites, to the polls for the first time, especially women, who were first allowed to vote in 1920.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] He lost important Democratic constituencies in the rural North as well as in Southern cities and suburbs.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith did retain the loyalty of the Deep South, thanks in part to the appeal of his running mate, Senator Joseph Robinson from Arkansas, but lost five states of the Rim South to Hoover.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith carried the popular vote in each of America's ten most populous cities, an indication of the rising power of the urban areas and their new demographics.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] His campaign theme song, "The Sidewalks of New York", had little appeal among rural Americans, who also found his 'city' accent slightly foreign when heard on radio.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith narrowly lost his home state; New York's electors were biased in favor of rural upstate and largely Protestant districts.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] However, in 1928, his fellow Democrat Franklin D.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Roosevelt (a Protestant of Dutch old-line stock) was elected to replace him as governor of New York.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Farley left Smith's camp to run Roosevelt's successful campaign for governor in 1928, and then Roosevelt's successful campaigns for the Presidency in 1932 and 1936.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Some political scientists believe that the 1928 election started a voter realignment that helped develop Roosevelt's New Deal coalition.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Lichtman notes that the sole defining issue of the election was anti-Catholicism, which radically realigned states' voting patterns.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] States that had never voted Republican after Reconstruction, such as Texas, Florida, North Carolina and Virginia, voted for Hoover, while Smith carried Massachusetts and Rhode Island—states that had never voted Democratic before save for 1912.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Lichtman further proves this by pointing out that Smith and Hoover had very similar political views save for religion and Prohibition, and yet the 1928 election had a turnout of 57%, despite previous 1920s American elections having their turnouts below 50%.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Finan (2003) says Smith is an underestimated symbol of the changing nature of American politics in the first half of the last century.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] He represented the rising ambitions of urban, industrial America at a time when the hegemony of rural, agrarian America was in decline, although many states had legislatures and congressional delegations biased toward rural areas due to a lack of redistricting after censuses.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith was connected to the hopes and aspirations of immigrants, especially Catholics and Jews from eastern and southern Europe.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith was a devout Catholic, but his struggles against religious bigotry were often misinterpreted when he fought the religiously inspired Protestant morality imposed by prohibitionists.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] The 1928 election initiated a complete voter realignment of African-Americans, who overwhelmingly supported the Republican Party prior to 1928.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Hoover sought "Southern Strategy" for the election, and sided with the segregationist lily-white Republicans at the expense of the pro-civil rights black and tans.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Prominent African Americans were removed from positions of leadership in the Republican Party and replaced with lily-white Republicans in order to appeal to the segregationist South, and Hoover's spokesmen in the South spoke of his commitment to white supremacy.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Al Smith was supportive of racial equality and appointed African Americans to the New York City school system and the New York City Civil Service Commission.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith attracted the attention of disheartened African-American voters, as he was unpopular in the South, faced prejudice as a Catholic, and had a reputation of a "spokesman for ethnic minorities in Northern cities".
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] As such, Smith's candidacy, coupled with Hoover's Southern concession, initiated abandonment of loyalty to the Republicans and embrace of the Democratic Party by African-American voters.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith was also known as an economic progressive, and championed progressive reforms such as a shorter workweek, workers' compensation laws, as well as health and workplace safety reforms.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Many of his reforms later inspired the New Deal, even though Smith himself came to oppose the New Deal legislation.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] However, Smith said little about his economic progressivism on the 1928 campaign trail, as the public was largely supportive of the conservative economic vision that the incumbent Republican administration pursued, crediting it with the economic prosperity at the time.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith felt slighted by Roosevelt during the latter's governorship.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] They became rivals in the 1932 Democratic Party presidential primaries after Smith decided to run for the nomination against Roosevelt, the presumed favorite.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] At the convention, Smith's animosity toward Roosevelt was so great that he put aside longstanding rivalries to work with McAdoo and Hearst to block Roosevelt's nomination for several ballots.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] That coalition fell apart when Smith refused to work on finding a compromise candidate; instead, he maneuvered to become the nominee.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] After losing the nomination, Smith eventually campaigned for Roosevelt in 1932, giving a particularly important speech on behalf of the Democratic nominee at Boston on October 27 in which he "pulled out all the stops".
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith became highly critical of Roosevelt's New Deal policies, which he deemed a betrayal of good-government progressive ideals and ran counter to the goal of close cooperation with business.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith joined the American Liberty League, an organization founded by conservative Democrats who disapproved of Roosevelt's New Deal measures and tried to rally public opinion against the New Deal.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] The League published pamphlets and sponsored radio programs, arguing that the New Deal was destroying personal liberty; however, the League failed to gain support in the 1934 or 1936 elections and rapidly declined in influence.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith's antipathy to Roosevelt and his policies was so great that he supported Republican presidential nominees Alf Landon in the 1936 election and Wendell Willkie in the 1940 election.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] According to Jonathan Alter, the reasons for Smith's opposition to Roosevelt's New Deal were principally personal rather than ideological.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Roosevelt wronged Smith in 1931 by opposing the proposal for an unequivocal stand for repeal of Prohibition postulated by Smith and his Northern progressive wing of the party.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Moreover, many of Smith's proposals and policies from his time as governor of New York were expanded and turned into federal legislation within the New Deal, leading Smith to believe that Roosevelt stole his ideas and was taking credit for them at his expense.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Speaking of Roosevelt in 1932, Smith proclaimed: "Frank Roosevelt just threw me out of a window." Smith later abandoned his criticism of the New Deal once Roosevelt arranged for the Reconstruction Finance Corporation to rent space in the Empire State Building, which eased Smith's financial problems.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Although personal resentment was one factor in Smith's break with Roosevelt and the New Deal, Christopher Finan (2003) argues that Smith was consistent in his beliefs and politics, suggesting that Smith always believed in social mobility, economic opportunity, religious tolerance, and individualism.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith was also far less supportive of direct federal intervention, on which "he was ambivalent, even uncertain." Despite the break between the men, Smith and Eleanor Roosevelt remained close.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] In 1936, while Smith was in Washington, D.C., making a vehement radio attack on the President, she invited him to stay at the White House.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] To avoid embarrassing the Roosevelts, he declined.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Historian Robert Slayton observes that Smith and Roosevelt did not reconcile until a brief meeting in June 1941, and he also suggests that during the early 1940s, the antipathy which Smith held toward his former ally had waned.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Upon the death of Smith's wife, Katie, in May 1944, Roosevelt sent Smith a note of personal condolence.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith's grandchildren later recalled that he was greatly touched by it.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] After the 1928 election, Smith became the president of Empire State, Inc., the corporation that built and operated the Empire State Building.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Construction for the building symbolically began on March 17, 1930, St.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Patrick's Day, per Smith's instructions.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith's grandchildren cut the ribbon when the world's tallest skyscraper opened on May 1, 1931, which was May Day, an international labor celebration.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Its construction had been completed in only 13 months, a record for such a large project.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] As with the Brooklyn Bridge, which Smith had seen being built from his Lower East Side boyhood home, the Empire State Building was both a vision and an achievement that had been constructed by combining the interests of all, rather than being divided by the interests of a few.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith continued to promote the Empire State Building, which was derided as the "Empty State Building" due to a lack of tenants, in the years following its construction.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] In 1929, Smith was awarded the Laetare Medal by the University of Notre Dame, considered the most prestigious award for American Catholics.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] In 1929 Smith was elected President of the Board of Trustees of the New York State College of Forestry at Syracuse University.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Knowing his fondness for animals, in 1934 Robert Moses made Al Smith the Honorary Night Zookeeper of the newly renovated Central Park Zoo.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Though a ceremonial title, Smith was given keys to the zoo and often took guests to see the animals after hours.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith was an early and vocal critic of the Nazi regime in Germany.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] He supported the Anti-Nazi boycott of 1933 and addressed a mass-meeting at Madison Square Garden against Nazism that March.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] His speech was included in the 1934 anthology *Nazism: An Assault on Civilization*.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] In 1938, Smith took to the airwaves to denounce Nazi brutality in the wake of *Kristallnacht*.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] His words were published in *The New York Times* article "Text of the Catholic Protest Broadcast" of November 17, 1938.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Like most New York City businessmen, Smith enthusiastically supported American military involvement in World War II.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Although he was not asked by Roosevelt to play any role in the war effort, Smith was an active and vocal proponent of FDR's attempts to amend the Neutrality Act in order to allow "Cash and Carry" sales of war equipment to be made to the British.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith spoke on behalf of the policy in October 1939, to which FDR responded directly: "Very many thanks.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] In 1939, Smith was appointed a Papal Chamberlain of the Sword and Cape, one of the highest honors which the Papacy bestowed on a layman.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Smith died at the Rockefeller Institute Hospital on October 4, 1944, of a heart attack, at the age of 70.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] He had been broken-hearted over the death of his wife from cancer five months earlier, on May 4, 1944.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] Patrick's Cathedral and is interred at Calvary Cemetery.
[src:charles-m-schwab/al-smith] On May 6, 1900, Al Smith married Catherine Ann Dunn, with whom he had five children.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-davison-bailey] Bailey was born in what is now Salem Lakes, Wisconsin, son of Eugene M.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-davison-bailey] He obtained his BSc in Mechanical Engineering in 1903 from the Lewis Institute in Chicago, now Illinois Institute of Technology.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-davison-bailey] Before his graduation Bailey had started his career as draftsman at the U.S Wind Engine and Pump Company in Batavia, Illinois, and had been trouble man at the Evanston Heating Co. in Evanston, Illinois.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-davison-bailey] After his graduation Bailey started his lifelong career at the Chicago Edison Co., soon to be Commonwealth Edison.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-davison-bailey] From 1903 to 1905 he started as draftsman, from 1906 to 1916 he was assistant chief engineer at Fisk Street Station, and another chief engineer.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-davison-bailey] From 1921 to 1932 he was superintendent of generating stations of the company, and in 1933 appointed assistant chief operating engineer.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-davison-bailey] From 1936 to 1942 he was chief operating engineer and manager of the Super Power department.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-davison-bailey] The last years ten years at the company he was vice-president in charge of operations and engineering.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-davison-bailey] He retired on February 1, 1952 after 48 years of service.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-davison-bailey] In 1942 Bailey had been awarded the Honorary Doctor of Science by the Northwestern University.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-dow] Dow was born in Glasgow, Scotland as son of William Dow, a blacksmith, and Jean (Keppy) Dow in 1862.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-dow] He emigrated to the US in 1882 at the age of twenty.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-dow] In 1893 Dow was appointed the first plant manager of the first municipally owned power plant in Detroit, and electrical engineer for the city of Detroit.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-dow] The power plant had been built as a result of Hazen Pingree's efforts to break the power of corporations over Detroit City politics.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-dow] It was during this time that Henry Ford worked under Dow at one of the Detroit Edison substations.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-dow] Dow took Ford with him to the 1896 annual convention of the Association of Edison Illuminating Companies being held that year in New York City.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-dow] It was at this convention that Dow introduced Ford to Thomas Edison, the meeting with, and encouragement from, the great scientist becoming a great inspiration to Ford in completing his first car.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-dow] Dow was appointed water commissioner for the city of Detroit in 1916-1921 and again in 1925-1932.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-dow] In 1932, he was made the president of Detroit Edison and served until 1940.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-dow] He was elected president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers for the 1928-1929 year.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-dow] He was a member of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, American Society of Civil Engineers, American Institute of Electrical Engineers, Institute of Electrical Engineers (Great Britain), Institute of Mechanical Engineers (Great Britain).
[src:charles-m-schwab/alex-dow] Dow also served as the President of The Engineering Society of Detroit from 1900-1901.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was born in Edinburgh, Scotland on 30 March 1851 to Edward Rupert Humphreys, an English classical scholar and profound educator, and Margaret McNutt of Prince Edward Island.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He attended his father's school in Boston after coming to the United States in 1859.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] At the age of fourteen he received an appointment and passed preliminary entrance exams for the United States Naval Academy before the academy discovered he was too young to complete entrance.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He instead began working for insurance companies and was made Secretary-Treasurer of the New York Guaranty and Indemnity Company by 1872, he became superintendent shortly thereafter.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He later became superintendent of the Bayonne and Greenville Gas Light Company and attended Stevens Institute of Technology earning his degree in mechanical engineering; he graduated in 1881.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1892 he founded Humphreys & Glasgow, Engineering, London and New York with Arthur G.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys continued his career with the Pintsch Lighting Company of New York, the United Gas Improvement Company, and the Weisbach Incandescent Gas Company.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In April 1872 he married Miss Eva Guillandeu of Bergen Point, NJ.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] They had three children in total: Harold, Crombie and Dorothy Caroline Humphreys-Turnbull.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of his son Harold, who was also the first son of a Stevens alumnus to graduate from the college, he endowed the Harold Humphreys Scholarship in 1902.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of Crombie, who drowned with Harold in the Nile in 1901, the Crombie Humphreys Scholarship in 1904.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1927, Alexander Crombie Humphreys lost a battle with cancer.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] His death came two years after serving as President of his Alma mater for a quarter of a century, and chairman of the board of trustees for two years.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] The only immediate family member to outlive him was his daughter.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Following the death of Henry Morton in 1902, the board of trustees of Stevens Institute of Technology unanimously called upon Humphreys to serve his Alma mater as president.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Prior to his presidency, Humphreys was elected a trustee of the institute on 23 December 1891 and served as chair of the Stevens Alumni Association from 1883 to 1886.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys developed the institute as one of the first technical schools in the United States.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During a dinner following his inauguration, Colonel Edwin A.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, Jr., son of the school's founder Edwin A.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, presented the institute with a plot of land on which to construct a dormitory.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon assuming the office of President, Humphreys requested of Andrew Carnegie the financial support to construct a new building.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He followed this with an address to the Board of Trustees urging construction of the Morton Laboratory of Chemistry, a dormitory, a gymnasium and library – a "crying need of the Institute".
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] As a homage to his predecessor, Humphreys campaigned for the creation of the Morton Memorial Chemistry Laboratory and commissioned a book on Stevens' founding and its early years to be named in his honor.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] These initiatives were but foreshadowing of the growth Humphreys would bring to Stevens.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1924 the campus grew from just over a city block to 23-acres, enrollment quadrupled and endowment grew to $2,864,000 (from $384,800 when Humprheys took office).
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] That year also marked the successful end of the "Million Dollar Campaign", which had attracted donations from alumni as well as George Eastman and Edward Harkness.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1909, Stevens seized the opportunity to acquire Castle Point from Richard Stevens inclusive of the prominent Stevens Family Castle constructed in 1853; the purchase was primarily funded by the Carnegie Foundation and John D.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] This came within months of acquiring the land adjacent to present-day 8th street upon which fraternity houses were constructed that stand to this day.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1960 the Institute expanded again and constructed two residence halls, one of which bared his name.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the growth of the institute, Alexander C.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys felt it important to impart engineering students with a sense of business – a tool that would be essential in their success in all lines of manufacturing.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He began teaching the first courses on this topic in 1903 and is regarded as the father of Engineering Economics.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] To honor his contributions, Stevens Institute of Technology endows an Alexander Crombie Humphreys Chair in Economics of Engineering.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the dinner of his inauguration, Humphreys announced that one of his ambitions was to start an Honor System at Stevens to cover academic work.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was very adamant that the creation of such a system come from the students and on the first page of the first issue of the school newspaper "The Stute" appeared an article written by a junior urging the implementation of such.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1908 the students created a self run Honor Board who was charged with investigating cases, bringing up charges, judging cases by a vote and recommend punishments to the faculty.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon Humphreys' recommendation, faculty were also required to abide by such a pledge in administering exams within Honor Board guidelines on the grounds that it is a "...proviso apply[ing] to the examiner as well as to the student".
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-graham-christie] Christie was born in Manchester, Ontario, Canada to Peter Christie and Mary Honor (Graham) Christie.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-graham-christie] He obtained his MSc in mechanical engineering at the School of Practical Science at the University of Toronto in 1901.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-graham-christie] After his graduation Christie started as an apprentice in the engineering shop of the Westinghouse Machine Company.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-graham-christie] After the introduction of its first steam turbine, Christie specialized in that field.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-graham-christie] By 1909 he was research Assistant in Steam and Gas Engineering at the University of Wisconsin, and associate professor of Steam and Gas Engineering by 1914.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-graham-christie] In 1914 he moved to the Johns Hopkins University, where he became associate professor, and later Professor of Engineering until his retirement in 1948, and director of the McCoy College until 1953.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-graham-christie] In 1939-40 Christie served as president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-graham-christie] He was awarded the honorary doctor in engineering by the Stevens Institute of Technology in 1939, and by the Lehigh University in 1940.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-graham-christie] The American Society for Engineering Education awarded Christie the Lamme Gold Medal in 1948, and the first George Westinghouse Gold Medal for engineering by the ASME in 1953.
[src:charles-m-schwab/alexander-graham-christie] At the Johns Hopkins Whiting school of Engineer an annual lecture is held on his behalf, the Alexander Graham Christie Lecture.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Schwab was born in Williamsburg, Pennsylvania, on February 18, 1862, the son of Pauline (née Farabaugh) and John Anthony Schwab.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] All four of his grandparents were Roman Catholic immigrants from Germany.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Schwab was raised in Loretto, Pennsylvania, which he considered his hometown.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] His father, John, operated a livery stable in Loretto and also served as a mail-carrier.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Schwab graduated from Saint Francis College in Loretto in 1877.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Schwab began his career as an engineer in Andrew Carnegie's steelworks, starting as a stake-driver in the engineering corps of the Edgar Thomson Steel Works and Furnaces in Braddock, Pennsylvania.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] He was promoted often, including to the positions of general superintendent of Homestead Works in 1887, and general superintendent of the Edgar Thomson Steel Works in 1890.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] In 1897, at only 35 years of age, he became president of the Carnegie Steel Company.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] In 1901, he helped negotiate the secret sale of Carnegie Steel to a group of New York City–based financiers, led by J.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] After the buyout, Schwab became the first president of the United States Steel Corporation, the company formed out of Carnegie's former holdings.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] In 1903, after several clashes with Morgan and fellow US Steel executive Elbert Gary, Schwab left the company to run the Bethlehem Shipbuilding and Steel Company, which ultimately became Bethlehem Steel, in Bethlehem, Pennsylvania.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] The company had shipyards in California, Delaware, and New Jersey through its brief but fortunate involvement as one of the few solvent enterprises in United States Shipbuilding Company.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Under Schwab's leadership and that of Eugene Grace, Bethlehem Steel emerged as one of the largest independent steel producers in the world.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] A major part of the company's success was the development of the H-beam, a precursor of today's ubiquitous I-beam.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Schwab was interested in mass-producing the wide flange steel beam, but that was a risky venture that required raising capital and building a large new plant, all to make a product whose ability to sell was unproven.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] In 1908, Bethlehem Steel began making the beam, which revolutionized building construction and contributed to the age of the skyscraper.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Its success helped make Bethlehem Steel the second-largest steel company in the world.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Bethlehem, Pennsylvania, was incorporated, virtually as a company town, by uniting four previous villages.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] In 1910, Schwab broke the Bethlehem Steel strike by calling out the newly formed Pennsylvania State Police.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Schwab successfully kept labor unions out of Bethlehem Steel throughout his tenure, although Bethlehem Steel unionized in 1941, two years after his death.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] In 1911, Bethlehem Steel formed a company soccer team known as Bethlehem Steel F.C.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Three years later, in 1914, Schwab took the team professional.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Until its demise in 1930, the team won eight league championships, six American Cups, and five National Challenge Cups.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] It was considered among the greatest soccer teams in U.S. history.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] The company disbanded the team as a result of financial losses incurred during the internecine 1928–1929 "Soccer Wars" between American Soccer League and United States Football Association and the onset of the Great Depression in 1929.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] During the first years of World War I, Bethlehem Steel had a virtual monopoly in contracts to supply the Allies with certain kinds of munitions.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] During this period, Schwab made many visits to Europe in connection with the manufacture and supply of munitions to the Allied governments.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] He circumvented American neutrality laws by funneling goods through Canada.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] On April 16, 1918, Schwab became director general of Emergency Fleet Corporation, a board granted by Congress with master authority over all shipbuilding in the United States.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] He was appointed over Charles Piez, the former general manager of the corporation.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] President Wilson had specifically asked Schwab to assume this responsibility.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Schwab's biggest change to the shipbuilding effort was to abandon the cost plus profit contracting system that had been in place up to that time and begin issuing fixed-price contracts.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] After America's entry into the war, he was accused of profiteering but was later acquitted.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Schwab was considered to be a risk taker and was highly controversial; Thomas Edison once famously called him the "master hustler".
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Schwab's lucrative contract providing steel to the Trans-Siberian Railroad came after he provided a $200,000 "gift" to the mistress of the Grand Duke Alexis Aleksandrovich.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] His innovative ways of dealing with his staff are given a mention in Dale Carnegie's most famous work, *How to Win Friends and Influence People*, published in 1936.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] In 1928, Schwab was awarded the Bessemer Gold Medal for "outstanding services to the steel industry".
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] In 1932, he was awarded the Melchett Medal by the British Institute of Fuel.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] In 1982, Schwab was inducted into the Junior Achievement U.S.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] In 2011, Schwab was inducted into the inaugural class of the American Metal Market Hall of Fame for his lifelong work in the U.S. steel industry.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Schwab lived in Weatherly, Pennsylvania, and donated $85,000 to build a school there.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] He moved to New York City's Upper West Side, which at the time was considered the "wrong" side of Central Park, where he built "Riverside", the most ambitious private house ever built in New York City.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] The $7 million 75-room house, designed by French architect Maurice Hébert, combined details from three French chateaux on a full city block.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] After Schwab's death, Mayor Fiorello La Guardia turned down a proposal to make Riverside the official mayoral residence, deeming it too grandiose.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] It was eventually razed and replaced by an apartment block.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Schwab also owned a 44-room summer estate on 1,000 acres (4 km2) in Loretto, Pennsylvania, called "*Immergrün*", German for "evergreen".
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] The house featured opulent gardens and a nine-hole golf course.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Rather than raze the existing house, Schwab had the mansion moved 200 feet (61 m) on rollers to a new location to make room for the new mansion.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Schwab's estate sold Immergrün after his death, and it is now Mount Assisi Friary owned by the Franciscan friars (Third Order Regular) who administer the adjacent Saint Francis University.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] The golf course, now known as “Immergrun Golf Club”, designed in 1917 by Donald Ross, is owned and operated by the university.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] The gardens feature a cascading fountain modeled after features at Versailles and include sculptures by Paul Manship, known for the Prometheus sculpture at Rockefeller Center in Manhattan.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Schwab became notorious for his "fast lane" lifestyle including opulent parties, high-stakes gambling, and a string of extramarital affairs producing at least one child out of wedlock.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] The affairs and the out-of-wedlock child soured his relationship with his wife.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] He became an international celebrity when he "broke the bank" at Monte Carlo, and traveled in a $100,000 private rail car named "Loretto".
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] He appeared in the 1918 film *The Yellow Dog*.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Even before the Great Depression, he had already spent most of his fortune, estimated at between $25 million and $40 million.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Adjusted for inflation in the first decade of the 21st century, that equates to between $500 million and $800 million.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] The stock market crash of 1929 finished off what years of wanton spending had started.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] He spent his last years in a small apartment.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] He could no longer afford the taxes on "Riverside", and it was seized by creditors.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] He had offered to sell the mansion at a huge loss but there were no buyers.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] At his death ten years later, Schwab's holdings in Bethlehem Steel were virtually worthless, and he was over $300,000 in debt.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Had he lived a few more years, he would have seen his fortunes restored when Bethlehem Steel was flooded with orders for war material.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Schwab had no children by Emma Dinkey, but had one daughter by a mistress.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Müller-Ury also painted his nephew and namesake Charles M.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Schwab, son of his brother Joseph, as a boy in a sailor suit around the same date.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Schwab died nine months later, on September 18 of that year, of heart disease at his apartment on Park Avenue in New York City.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Patrick's Cathedral and about 2,000 people were estimated to line the streets of the procession.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] Rockefeller Jr., and Charles Evans Hughes were among those in attendance at his funeral.
[src:charles-m-schwab/charles-m-schwab] He was originally interred at the Gate of Heaven Cemetery in Hawthorne, New York, but his remains were moved on April 29, 1940, to a private mausoleum at Saint Michael Catholic Church Cemetery in Loretto, Pennsylvania.
